.\" lispbar-themes(7) - lispbar theme authoring guide
.TH LISPBAR-THEMES 7 "May 2026" "lispbar" "Miscellaneous"
.SH NAME
lispbar-themes \- built-in themes and how to write your own
.SH SYNOPSIS
.EX
;; ~/.config/lispbar/themes/MY-THEME.lisp
(in-package :lispbar)

(define-theme :MY-NAME
  :bg     '(R G B A)
  :normal '(R G B A)
  :accent '(R G B A)
  :ok     '(R G B A)
  :warn   '(R G B A)
  :urgent '(R G B A)
  :muted  '(R G B A))
.EE
where R G B A are doubles in 0.0\(en1.0.
.SH DESCRIPTION
A Lispbar theme is a property list mapping
.B face
keywords to
.B (R G B A)
colour tuples.  Modules return text in named faces
.RB ( :accent ,
.BR :urgent ", ...);"
the active theme decides what each face actually looks like.  This
is what makes one-keyword theme switching work.
.SH FACES
.PP
.TS
allbox tab(|);
l l.
:bg|bar background
:normal|default text colour
:accent|emphasis (clock, focused workspace)
:ok|positive states (charging, connected)
:warn|low / cautionary states
:urgent|critical states (battery <10%, errors)
:muted|secondary text (separators, "off", brackets)
.TE
.PP
Omitted faces fall back to the active theme's
.BR :normal .
.SH BUILT-IN THEMES
.BR :default ", " :minimal ", " :nordish ", " :gruvboxish ", " :catppuccinish ", " :doomish .
.PP
List the live inventory:
.EX
$ lispbar --list-themes
.EE
.SH EXAMPLE
.EX
;; ~/.config/lispbar/themes/dracula.lisp
(in-package :lispbar)

(define-theme :dracula
  :bg     '(0.157 0.165 0.212 1.0)
  :normal '(0.945 0.945 0.945 1.0)
  :accent '(0.741 0.576 0.976 1.0)
  :ok     '(0.314 0.980 0.482 1.0)
  :warn   '(0.945 0.980 0.549 1.0)
  :urgent '(1.000 0.333 0.333 1.0)
  :muted  '(0.380 0.420 0.490 1.0))
.EE
Reference it from
.IR config.lisp :
.EX
(theme :dracula)
.EE
.SH CONVERTING FROM HEX
For #RRGGBB, divide each pair by 255:
.EX
#1e1e2e  ->  (0.118 0.118 0.184 1.0)
#cdd6f4  ->  (0.804 0.839 0.957 1.0)
#89b4fa  ->  (0.537 0.706 0.980 1.0)
.EE
A quick shell helper:
.EX
hex2rgba() {
  s="${1#\\#}"
  printf '%.3f %.3f %.3f 1.0\\n' \\
    "$(echo $((16#${s:0:2})) / 255 | bc -l)" \\
    "$(echo $((16#${s:2:2})) / 255 | bc -l)" \\
    "$(echo $((16#${s:4:2})) / 255 | bc -l)"
}
.EE
